Roll Edition Format

Schema documentation for the linked-rolls piano roll edition format.

The root element of this format is an Edition, describing a specific digital edition of a piano roll (cf. lrm:F2 Expression). It consists of the following properties:

root copies
Type: array

The physical roll copies on which this edition is based.

 No Additional Items

Each item of this array must be:

root copies RollCopy
Type: object

A physical copy of a roll, held at a specific location. Each roll copy has its own set of features, measurements, conditions, and modifications. Multiple copies of the same roll may exist across different archives or collections.

crm:E22 Human-Made Object

root copies copies items conditions
Type: array

Condition assessments of this roll copy (e.g. paper stretch, general wear). Each condition is an assumption annotatable with a belief.

 No Additional Items

Each item of this array must be:

root copies copies items conditions RollConditionAssignment
Type: object

An assignment of a condition (general or paper-stretch) to a roll copy, annotatable with a belief about its certainty.

  • Option 1
  • Option 2
root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0
Type: object

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation
Type: object

An optional annotation expressing a belief about this assumption. Uses the JSON-LD-star @annotation mechanism to attach epistemic metadata (certainty and reasons) to any triple.

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief
Type: object

A belief is a temporal object and associates a proposition (i.e. a statement) with a certainty. It comes into existence through argumentations (reasons).

crminf:I2 Belief

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief certainty
Type: enum (of string)

The level of certainty associated with this belief.

crminf:J5 holds to be

Must be one of:

  • "true"
  • "likely"
  • "possible"
  • "unlikely"
  • "false"

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons
Type: array

The argumentations providing reasons for this belief.

crminf:J2 was concluded by
 No Additional Items

Each item of this array must be:

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons AnyArgumentation
Type: object

An argumentation can be either a plain argumentation, a meaning comprehension, an inference, or a belief adoption.

  • MeaningComprehension
  • Inference
  • BeliefAdoption
  • Argumentation
root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons reasons items anyOf MeaningComprehension
Type: object

A meaning comprehension interprets or disambiguates the meaning of symbols or features. For example, interpreting a pencil mark as an instruction to add or remove a perforation or as the dating of the roll.

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons reasons items anyOf item 0 actor
Type: object

The person who carried out this activity.

crm:P14 carried out by

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons reasons items anyOf item 0 actor name
Type: string

The full name of the person.

rdfs:label
Example:

"Grnfeld, Alfred"

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons reasons items anyOf item 0 actor role
Type: string

The role of the person in the context of the edition, e.g. 'pianist', 'editor', 'publisher', etc.

root copies copies items conditions conditions items anyOf item 0 @annotation belief reasons reasons items anyOf item 0 actor sameAs
Type: array of string

This property can be used to point to a GND, Wikidata, or similar entry.

Specific value: "paper-stretch"

root copies copies items features
Type: array

Provides a reconstructed version of the roll, with shift, stretch and emendations already taken into account. This property will not be exported in the final JSON.

 No Additional Items

Each item of this array must be:

root copies copies items features AnyFeature
Type: object

The union of all physical feature types that can appear on a roll: holes (perforations), writings (labels, annotations), marks (pencil, ink), and glued-on patches (paper, tape).

  • Hole
  • Writing
  • Mark
  • GluedOn
root copies copies items features features items anyOf Hole
Type: object

A hole (perforation) in the roll paper. Holes are the primary carriers of musical information on piano rolls, as they trigger notes and expression controls when passing over the tracker bar.

root copies copies items features features items anyOf item 0 condition
Type: object

This can be used e.g. to indicate a perforation which is torn out or in any other way damaged.

The punching pattern of the hole. Regular holes have evenly-spaced bridges, accelerating holes have decreasing bridge widths, and staggering holes alternate between adjacent tracks (cf. Phillips).

 No Additional Items

root roll recordingEvent created edits Edit
Type: object

A set of edits transforms a version of a roll into another version. Edits insert or delete symbols, or both (= replace). Edits may be motivated by a given set of reasons, e.g. to add an additional accent or to correct an error. If an edit is the interpretation of a metamark, such as a pencil mark, this should be made explicit using a meaning comprehension on the @annotation field.
